-- BHP, Rio, Western Areas, Santos, Spark, Woodside: Australian Stock Preview
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-06-29T22:08:03Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-29/bhp-rio-western-areas-santos-spark-woodside-australian-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed yesterday. All
prices are from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  
 The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in September
slipped 2.1 percent to 4,245 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank
of New York Australia ADR Index  slumped 5.1 percent. The  S&P/ASX
200 Index  declined 0.9 percent to 4,345.70.  
 Mining shares: Copper prices fell the most in five weeks in
New York after reports signaled a deteriorating economic outlook
in China and the U.S., the world’s top metals buyers.  
 BHP Billiton  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
lost 1 percent to A$38.10 in Sydney. Its American depositary
receipts plunged 5 percent in New York trading.  
 Rio Tinto Group (RIO AU), the world’s third-largest mining
company, retreated 0.3 percent to A$68.42 in Sydney.  
 Australia’s government may unveil a compromise for its
proposed mining tax as soon as today after seeking support for
the plan from resources companies, the Australian Financial
Review reported, without saying where it got the information.  
 Oil companies: Crude oil fell by the most in more than
three weeks in New York as China’s economy grew at the slowest
pace in five months in April and confidence among U.S. consumers
declined more than forecast.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, slipped 1.6 percent to A$42.57,
and rival Santos Ltd. (STO AU) declined 0.6 percent to A$12.59.  
 Fortescue Metals Group Ltd.  (FMG AU): Australia’s third-
largest iron-ore miner said new Prime Minister  Julia Gillard 
must make more concessions on a planned mining tax than
canvassed by her predecessor  Kevin Rudd . The stock fell 2.5
percent to A$4.31.  
 Spark Infrastructure  (SKI AU): The Australian company that
invests in utility infrastructure assets has entered into a
refinancing deal covering all its existing bank debt facilities,
it said in a statement to the Australian Stock Exchange. Spark
declined 3.8 percent to A$1.145.  
      Western Areas NL  (WSA AU): The company, a nickel supplier
to BHP Billiton, was raised to “buy” from “hold” at Deutsche
Bank AG. Western Areas shares lost 3.3 percent to A$3.77.  
